The constitutional makers were not some of our current politicians today descended from on high, but rather they had their hand in the cookie jar. So, that was part of my understanding too of political economy.

173
00:29:39,720 --> 00:29:45,720
Did you ever visit the first red-backed in the court?

174
00:29:45,720 --> 00:30:06,720
No, no, I don't even know where it was. No. No, I, in fact, by the time Carl and I visited their wallpour, and I think the two of us were there together, I never visited Bill there alone, then he and Wendy were married by the time I was making trips to the coast to visit them.

175
00:30:06,720 --> 00:30:34,720
What Bill did was he bought two cabins, and then when he and Wendy were married, they built a petition which housed a kitchen, a small dining room, and so forth. And then one end became a study in their bedroom and the other end was a living room.

176
00:30:34,720 --> 00:30:55,720
And then eventually after we knew them several years, they built a bigger bedroom and a garage over the other end, but it was very livable and very appropriate for them. And it backed up right on a bluff over the ocean, as you probably know.

177
00:30:55,720 --> 00:31:04,720
We talked earlier about the order of quite a lot of study. I wanted to be thinking of reiterating your recollections and what that strike was like.

178
00:31:04,720 --> 00:31:08,720
This was not recorded though. That was over coffee.

179
00:31:08,720 --> 00:31:31,720
Osteer, Spartan, beautiful desk, bookcase, heartbound books, not many of them. The study was not filled with wall to wall books.

180
00:31:31,720 --> 00:31:43,720
It's the neatest study I've ever seen. It's probably an expression of Bill's work.

181
00:31:43,720 --> 00:31:49,720
You talked about this a little bit already, but how did the logistics work out of living on that building?

182
00:31:49,720 --> 00:32:00,720
Well, he had an agreement when he signed his contract that he wouldn't have to be here every day because he wanted to live on the coast.

183
00:32:00,720 --> 00:32:12,720
And I wanted to teach at Tuesday, Thursday schedule. And I know there was some resentment over that. I was privy to it.

184
00:32:12,720 --> 00:32:27,720
And I thought it was nonsense because it came from people who were doing nothing and had zero prestige in terms of the historical profession.

185
00:32:27,720 --> 00:32:42,720
And Bill gave his all to the department. He did his share, thought his fair share of classes. He advised students and we had individual student advising, although probably not too many.

186
00:32:42,720 --> 00:32:53,720
Students who matriculated in his class, undergraduates, I would say probably 98% of them never knew who they were taking the class with.

187
00:32:53,720 --> 00:33:09,720
And a striking example of this, I was attending a Western history meeting in Sacramento and I was in an elevator in a fellow saw my identification card for the conference.

188
00:33:09,720 --> 00:33:18,720
And asked me, he said, William Mappam Williams still teaching. And I said, yes.

189
00:33:18,720 --> 00:33:32,720
He said, you know, I had a class with him as an undergraduate and I never knew who he was. So that was kind of a, and I opened it for me. Well, it was something I never forgot because, you know, wow.

190
00:33:32,720 --> 00:33:36,720
So he would take the bus over in the morning teaching and make it back in?

191
00:33:36,720 --> 00:33:55,720
Yeah, and I think it was seven o'clock return bus and he would be home. Well, by the time I was here, he was living in Walport. And so he would leave his car in Newport or Wendy would drive picking him up and something like that.

192
00:33:55,720 --> 00:33:58,720
And so he didn't even know how that worked out.

193
00:33:58,720 --> 00:34:13,720
So he didn't even know how that worked out? No, he didn't. And when he did stay over, if he stayed over Tuesday and Wednesday night, because he had other commitments and he did that pretty regularly, he stayed at the townhouse.

194
00:34:13,719 --> 00:34:26,719
And it's still the townhouse, isn't it? And Southforth and it's Tommy's bar and grill. And then it was just the townhouse bar.

195
00:34:26,719 --> 00:34:32,719
And so we talked about the townhouse hotel or the other house.

196
00:34:32,719 --> 00:34:46,719
No, Crevall's hotel and I can't remember where we migrated for a while. And then the townhouse, we would get together there for drinks afterwards sometimes.

197
00:34:46,719 --> 00:34:52,719
Can't remember. There is now.

198
00:34:52,719 --> 00:35:04,719
Yeah, I'm watching. I've got about 18, 15 minutes or so.

199
00:35:04,719 --> 00:35:08,719
How do you characterize his work style?

200
00:35:08,719 --> 00:35:17,719
Well, I have to back up because by the time we were talking about writing drafts of papers and so forth.

201
00:35:17,719 --> 00:35:31,719
And he would use long yellow pads. He called it full scrap. And I don't know if that it's probably, you know, a early 20th century term.

202
00:35:31,719 --> 00:35:40,719
And I use the 8.5 by 11 pads now they're lined and so forth.

203
00:35:40,719 --> 00:35:55,719
And he used the longer ones, 14 inch, I suspect. And he would write drafts of material on that in long hand. And then he would transfer that.

204
00:35:55,719 --> 00:36:08,719
He would type it on a first rough draft after doing some editing. So by the time he was doing that it was more or less a third draft that he was typing by the time he did that.

205
00:36:08,719 --> 00:36:18,719
And I know that was part of his routine. And beyond that, you know, after he had, if he was writing, let's say, empires a way of life or something.

206
00:36:18,719 --> 00:36:33,719
The process of revision, you know, once he had a manuscript completed, you know, I tend to go back through chapters individually and then the whole manuscript.

207
00:36:33,719 --> 00:36:45,719
But that's, of course, I'm using computers and Bill never graduated to use the use of computers. But he was a fast typist too.

208
00:36:45,719 --> 00:36:53,719
And Prone, pretty ever free, I think. I mean, if you look at his typescripts, they're pretty good.

209
00:36:53,719 --> 00:36:58,719
So those three days in the cost for free generally devoted to reading, writing them?

210
00:36:58,719 --> 00:37:13,719
I would say yes. And some of it late night. You know, he tended to work at night. And that was a habit he developed, you know, probably when he taught at the Uvoa and certainly when he was in Madison.

211
00:37:13,719 --> 00:37:28,719
Yeah, he had a house full of children, you know, two of Carrins and then he and Carrin had three children at their home.

212
00:37:28,719 --> 00:37:35,719
And then he had some money that seems to have initially sort of presented having to do that, but maybe he came more from that.

213
00:37:35,719 --> 00:37:42,719
Yeah, I don't know. I think he worked, you know, I mean, you so incredibly productive then.

214
00:37:42,719 --> 00:37:50,719
In addition to turning out 42 PhDs and 11 years, you imagine that.

215
00:37:50,719 --> 00:38:04,719
Now some of them were still finishing up obviously when he was here. And I don't know when he told me at one point, you know, he had placed his last candidate.

216
00:38:04,719 --> 00:38:13,719
In a job. And that could have been the mid 70s and it might have been Peggy Morley or Henry Berger.

217
00:38:13,719 --> 00:38:24,719
He talked a bit about tragedy and contrary to the influential books. There's sort of a sense that his scholarship kind of declined over the time.

218
00:38:24,719 --> 00:38:30,719
The quality during the OSU, they do comment on that.

219
00:38:30,719 --> 00:38:41,719
Well, he said he would never write another book. And actually my wife and I called him on it when he published Empires A Way of Life.

220
00:38:41,719 --> 00:38:48,719
And actually America confronts a revolutionary world. I think he even made that comment before that book. But he didn't call those books.

221
00:38:48,719 --> 00:39:00,719
He called them extended essays. So there was a difference. And well, then you could call tragedy of American diplomacy, you know, an extended essay.

222
00:39:00,719 --> 00:39:13,719
Whether, you know, like his first book American Russian relations or roots of the modern American empire, which were detailed, annotated, documented books.

223
00:39:13,719 --> 00:39:23,719
Maybe he called those books. I don't know. But I would say I was never enamored by America confronts a revolutionary world.

224
00:39:23,719 --> 00:39:38,719
But Empires A Way of Life is an incredible piece of writing. And I was telling my friend, Sunday, a story who was visiting our home, that Empires A Way of Life.

225
00:39:38,719 --> 00:39:44,719
I don't know how many different languages has been translated into you probably know.

226
00:39:44,719 --> 00:39:58,719
Japanese, Chinese, Italian, German, French, add in some item. And it's a testimony to the influence of his career, the body of his work.

227
00:39:58,719 --> 00:40:08,719
And I think as a capsule, and my reading of Paul Biel kind of reminded me of this is how important that book is.

